      <section>
         <title>Transformer Output Voltage Calibration</title>
         <p>The
transformer is feedforward controlled. This means that the output
on the secondary side of the transformer is calculated based on the
actual measured current and compensated based on a stored characteristic
of the output transformer. The second regulator is the feedback controlled
outer control loop. This control loop is very slow and compensates
slow changes (temperature, ageing etc) to guarantee the 1% output
voltage tolerance. The transformer output voltage can be configured
as follows.<ol>
               <li>
                  <p>Set the UPS system in ‘standby state’. </p>
               </li>
               <li>
                  <p>Disable the outer control loop via the service port menu <menucascade>
                        <uicontrol>System calibration</uicontrol>
                        <uicontrol>System test function</uicontrol>
                        <uicontrol>Disable output transformer compensation</uicontrol>
                     </menucascade>.<note>Type two characters in: To activate function
two type in “02”.</note>
                  </p>
               </li>
               <li>
                  <p>After disabling the outer control loop, the system can be set
on. Configure the settings for the transformer output voltage as per
the table. If there is only resistive load available the 140% must
interpolated or the battery must be applied to help the input. Be
sure that the output current is already calibrated, so that the load
percentage is displayed correctly:<table outputclass="font:10" pgwide="1">
                        <tgroup cols="2">
                           <colspec colname="COLSPEC0"/>
                           <colspec colname="col1"/>
                           <thead>
                              <row>
                                 <entry valign="top">Setting </entry>
                                 <entry valign="top">Description</entry>
                              </row>
                           </thead>
                           <tbody>
                              <row>
                                 <entry>329</entry>
                                 <entry>TransformerOut
Volt at 20% load<footnote>Transformer voltage at 20% of nominal output current</footnote>
                                 </entry>
                              </row>
                              <row>
                                 <entry>330</entry>
                                 <entry>TransformerOut
Volt at 60% load</entry>
                              </row>
                              <row>
                                 <entry>331</entry>
                                 <entry>TransformerOut
Volt at 80% load</entry>
                              </row>
                              <row>
                                 <entry>332</entry>
                                 <entry>TransformerOut
Volt at 100% load</entry>
                              </row>
                              <row>
                                 <entry>333</entry>
                                 <entry>TransformerOut
Volt at 120% load</entry>
                              </row>
                              <row>
                                 <entry>334</entry>
                                 <entry>TransformerOut Volt at 140% load<footnote>To measure this value please
add a DC source otherwise it is not possible to support this load.</footnote>
                                 </entry>
                              </row>
                           </tbody>
                        </tgroup>
                     </table> It is independent if the load is resistive or has also an
inductive part. The relevant value to compensate the transformer is
the current and therefor the displayed load. It is not correct to
apply only 16% with resistive load to have the same compensation as
with 20% and PF 0.8 load.</p>
               </li>
               <li>
                  <p>After calibration, restart the system to enable the outer control
loop and activate the new settings.</p>
               </li>
            </ol>
         </p>
      </section>
      <section>
         <title>Outer Control Loop Calibration</title>
         <p>
            <note>Schneider
Electric does not recommend calibrating the outer control loop. Instead
It is preferred to do the transformer calibration very precisely.</note>The following settings are used for the outer control loop. For one
phase system the Ph-N voltage x 10 must be entered. For three phase
systems the Ph-Ph voltage x 10 must be entered.<table outputclass="font:10" pgwide="1">
               <tgroup cols="2">
                  <colspec colname="COLSPEC0"/>
                  <colspec colname="col1"/>
                  <thead>
                     <row>
                        <entry valign="top">Setting </entry>
                        <entry valign="top">Description</entry>
                     </row>
                  </thead>
                  <tbody>
                     <row>
                        <entry>398</entry>
                        <entry>Calibration OutVoltage
L12 / L1-N<footnote>Output voltage x 10</footnote>
                        </entry>
                     </row>
                     <row>
                        <entry>399</entry>
                        <entry>Calibration OutVoltage
L23 / L1-N</entry>
                     </row>
                     <row>
                        <entry>400</entry>
                        <entry>Calibration OutVoltage L31 / L1-N</entry>
                     </row>
                  </tbody>
               </tgroup>
            </table>One phase systems have standard values of 2200, 2300 and 2400
with 1:1 transformer. Three phase systems have standard values of
3800, 4000 and 4200 with 1:1 transformer. With all different transformers
values from 1000 to 7000 (100V to 700V) are possible. The outer control
loop is activated 5 seconds after turning on the system to avoid regulation
during startup ramp of output voltage. Too low voltages can be set
higher if the value in the outer control loop is set a bit higher.</p>
      </section>
      <section>
         <title>Charge Current Calibration</title>
         <p>The UPS system
uses two chargers to charge the batteries. These two chargers must
be calibrated to work together and share their load. Only one setting
is needed:<table outputclass="font:10" pgwide="1">
               <tgroup cols="2">
                  <colspec colname="COLSPEC0"/>
                  <colspec colname="col1"/>
                  <thead>
                     <row>
                        <entry valign="top">Setting </entry>
                        <entry valign="top">Description</entry>
                     </row>
                  </thead>
                  <tbody>
                     <row>
                        <entry>21</entry>
                        <entry>Charger offset<footnote>100 means no offset</footnote>
                        </entry>
                     </row>
                  </tbody>
               </tgroup>
            </table>If the charge current measured is higher than the displayed
current value the setting must also be lowered. A difference of 10
means approximately 0.7 A.</p>
